version: 1
display_name: VCFO-9X-000004 - The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations for Networks Platform NGINX server must implement HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) to protect the integrity of remote sessions of external server contexts.
global_description: |-
  HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) instructs web browsers to only use secure connections for all future requests when communicating with a web site. Doing so helps prevent SSL protocol attacks, SSL stripping, cookie hijacking, and other attempts to circumvent SSL protection.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFO-9X-000004
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000015-WSR-000014
  cci:
    - CCI-001453
  nist:
    - AC-17 (2)
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_operations_net_nginx:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations for Networks Platform NGINX server must implement HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) to protect the integrity of remote sessions of external server contexts.
    control_id: VCFO-9X-000004
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      Verify a header is present to configure HSTS.

      View the running configuration by running the following command:

      # nginx -T 2>&1 | sed -n '/server\s{/{:a;N;/.*location/!ba;/listen.*\sssl/p}'

      Example configuration:

      server {
      add_header Strict-Transport-Security max-age=15768000;
      }

      or

      server {
      add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000" always;
      }

      If an HSTS header is not configured for all servers and locations with SSL enabled, this is a finding.

      Note: There can be several add_header directives. These directives are inherited from the previous configuration level if and only if there are no add_header directives defined on the current level so care must be taken if add_header is defined at multiple levels to include headers configured at a higher level.
    rationale: |-
      HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) instructs web browsers to only use secure connections for all future requests when communicating with a web site. Doing so helps prevent SSL protocol attacks, SSL stripping, cookie hijacking, and other attempts to circumvent SSL protection.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      The /etc/nginx/sites-available/vnera file.

      Add or update the "add_header Strict-Transport-Security" directive for the server context listening on port 443, for example:

      server {
      listen 443 ssl http2;

      add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000" always;
      }

      Reload the NGINX configuration by running the following command:

      # nginx -s reload

      Note: There can be several add_header directives. These directives are inherited from the previous configuration level if and only if there are no add_header directives defined on the current level so care must be taken if add_header is defined at multiple levels to include headers configured at a higher level.
